{
  "texts": [
    "The complexity arises from multiple factors, including the need to gather data from diverse sources, the change of disease classification and coding systems over time, the dynamic nature of criteria for defining new cancer cases, and the difficulty in differentiating between new cases and recurrences or metastases of existing cases (Parkin, 2006).",
    "Therefore, the complexity of data collection, classification, validation and processing means that cancer incidence figures are available two to three years behind the calendar year.",
    "In this context, PBCRs are highly interested in using methods to forecast cancer incidence figures and a variety of methods have been proposed in the literature to produce such forecasts.",
    "For example, simple linear (Hakulinen and Dyba, 1994) and non-linear models (Dyba et al., 1997), join-point regression models (Kim et al., 2000), generalized additive models (Clements et al., 2005) or Lee-carter (LC) models (Lee and Carter, 1992).",
    "But the methods commonly used in the literature to get projections are based on Age-Period-Cohort (APC) models (Holford, 1983)."
  ]
}